There is an unfortunate tendency for Nationalists to mistake aesthetics for substance. Aesthetics are important as a propaganda tool and play a higher role in extolling the noble spirit, but aesthetics is essentially a mirage. With the proper lighting, enough practice and long enough running film, a good videographer can make even the most unassuming seem influential. Anyone who has met a fitness influencer in person can generally attest to this â€“ they are never as impressive looking in person. Substance is a much harder value to quantify. A man cannot tell you how reliable he is, he can only show it through action. Yes, there is always a need to consider the aesthetics of anything public facing, but what that is will change depending upon your audience. Substance however, does not change. Substance is the grit of a man and how much steel he has in his spine, it is a behaviour that can be learned only with great difficulty and careful cultivation, and ultimately depends on the factors that make a man who he is. In the vast majority of cases, substance is innate and unconscious. One should always look and dress well, but one should be concerned more with the substance of the men you recruit. A few young lads in trackies have done more to stop Plantation centres going up in their area than the dozens in brown shoes and polo necks. The latter is maybe more aesthetic to the middle class; the former is definitely the group with more substance to them.

In the 1976 German Grand Prix, Niki Lauda had a serious crash. His car plunged off the track and burst into flames. He was trapped in the burning vehicle for almost a minute before being pulled out by other drivers who stopped to rescue him. The accident left him with severe burns and iniuries. But 6 weeks after recovering in a hospital bed, Lauda surprised the world of motorsport by taking part in the Italian Grand Prix in Monza. Still in bandages after having suffered 1st- to 3rd degree burns over his face and hands, he finished 4th. One shocked journalist at the time wrote how he had seen Lauda peel blood-soaked bandages from his scalp after the race. The next season, in 1977, Lauda went on to win his second Formula One world championship. He then retired until he returned again and won his last world champion title in 1984. His comeback is a testament to his strength of character and his love for the sport. Niki Lauda's return is often seen as one of the most iconic moments in F1.
